Introduction

To solve this challenge, which is find the plankton label2 associated to a certain image, we chose to use convolutionnal neural network because it was the model we knew the less. To do so, we used the keras library.

In the notebook, you will find the following parts:

  • Data Exploration
    • Distribution of the different labels that the images are assigned to
    • Distribution of the different image dimensions
  • Data Pre-processing
    • Image size study
    • Image resizing
    • Data splitting
    • Data generation
  • Model selection
    • CNN
    • Dataset selection
    • Optimization as regards to hyper parameters
    • Test of different architectures
    • Model choice

import zipfile
from io import BytesIO
from PIL import Image

def extract_zip_to_memory(input_zip):
    '''
    This function extracts the images stored inside the given zip file.
    It stores the result in a python dictionary.
    
    input_zip (string): path to the zip file
    
    returns (dict): {filename (string): image_file (bytes)}
    '''
    input_zip=zipfile.ZipFile(input_zip)
    return {name: BytesIO(input_zip.read(name)) for name in input_zip.namelist() if name.endswith('.jpg')}

The images are to be in black and white, so we won't need to deal with colors. We can notice that images are very diversified with many different sizes. We'll have to deal with these oulier images, in order to scale correctly all our images with an appropriate size without loosing a lot of information (especially for the 2-3 types of plankton not well represented).

The goal is both to align images size and to minimize the weight of the images we are going to feed our model with, to optimize the duration of the computation and the results.

Let's analyse the different sizes of the images in order to know at which size we should sacle our images to loose minimum data.

Image resizing

In [7]:
def in_array(DF,size):
    '''
    Put the whole dataset into the right dimension and a np.array.
    arg:
        DF : dataframe with the object names associated with the level2 label.
        size: size of the wanted image side
    return:
        X: array of image array
    '''
    names = DF['objid'].astype('int').astype('str')
    
    #load the images
    img_files = extract_zip_to_memory("/mnt/datasets/plankton/flowcam/imgs.zip")
    
    X = []
    
    for i in tqdm(names):
        img = Image.open(img_files['imgs/'+i+'.jpg'])
        
        img = img.resize((size, size), Image.ANTIALIAS)
        X.append(np.array(img))
    
    del img_files #don't need that anymore
    X = np.array(X)
    
    #normalization: will be done later
    #X = (X-np.mean(X))/np.std(X)
    
    return X

def labeling2(DF):
    '''
    Put all the label into integers (between 1 and 39)
    '''
    #encoding the labels
    le=LabelEncoder()
    labels= DF['level2'].values
    Y = le.fit_transform(labels)
    #Y=to_categorical(Y,39)
    
    return Y

#Let's not use the whole data set for now, and make sure we don't always use the same images
def get_samples(X,Y,size):
    '''
    Return a number of random images with their label
    '''
    Z = np.random.permutation(list(zip(X,Y)))[:size]
    A,B = zip(*Z)
    A,B = np.array(A),np.array(B)
    return A,B

def get_train_test_sets(X,Y,IMG_SIZE):
    '''
    split the train dataset and reshape the train and test dataset
    '''
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,Y, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)
    x_train=x_train.reshape(-1,IMG_SIZE,IMG_SIZE,1)
    y_train=y_train.reshape(-1,1)
    x_test=x_test.reshape(-1,IMG_SIZE,IMG_SIZE,1)
    y_test=y_test.reshape(-1,1)
    return x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test

Data generation

The obvious lack of sample for some plankton type led us to consider generate data, using a keras class. There are two ways to do so. First, The ImageDataGenerator can be used to generate batch of data directly when the model is running but this implies that we don't have the choice of the image from which is generated. And we would like to only generated data from images of under-represented plankton. Also, as you will soon see, we didn't good results with this approach. That's why we developped our own function to transform our images (flip horizontal and vertical, and 45 rotation), still using the ImageDataGenerator class.

In [17]:
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
    featurewise_center=True,
    featurewise_std_normalization=True,
    rotation_range=20,
    width_shift_range=0.2,
    height_shift_range=0.2,
    horizontal_flip=True)
In [161]:
def less_represented_plankton(DF,size):
    metaDF_sort= DF[['objid','level2']].groupby('level2').count()
    metaDF_sort_best=metaDF_sort.sort_values(by='objid', ascending=True)[:size]
    metaDF_sort_best = list(metaDF_sort_best.index)
    
    #labelize
    labels = le.transform(metaDF_sort_best)
    
    return labels
In [322]:
def handmade_generation(X,Y,size,labels):
    '''
    labels: des chiffres et pas des lettres !
    '''
    #3 different tranformations
    dico = {}
    dico['flip_vertical']=True
    dic = {}
    dic['flip_horizontal']=True
    di = {}
    di['theta']=0.45
    
    new_X= []
    new_Y= []
    
    for n in range(len(X)):
        if len(new_X)<size: #To control the number of images to generate
            if Y[n][0] in labels: #To control which image to select
                new_X.append(datagen.apply_transform(X[n],dico))
                new_X.append(datagen.apply_transform(X[n],dic))
                new_X.append(datagen.apply_transform(X[n],di))
                new_Y.append(Y[n])
                new_Y.append(Y[n])
                new_Y.append(Y[n])
                
    new_X = np.array(new_X)
    new_Y = np.array(new_Y)
    return new_X,new_Y

Model Selection

As part of the model selection, we:

  • Chose a first model
  • Tried the different pre-processed datasets (with or without generated data and with or without normalization), we started to test our model with those different dataset and selected one
  • Optimized the hyperparameters
  • Tried differents architectures

Multi convolutionnal layer CNN

In our research, we found several ways to implement a CNN. The first we implemented was inspired from the following tutorial: https://towardsdatascience.com/image-classification-python-keras-tutorial-kaggle-challenge-45a6332a58b8. We chose this one because it was one of the easiest to understand and yet complexe enough. Also, its problem is quite the same as ours: classification of black and white images. The CNN is composed of several keras conv2D layers with different output size, maximum pooling and batch normalization which are three caracteristics proven to be most efficient in image classification. The model ends with a drop_out layer to reduce overfitting and two dense layer to cast the results into our labels.

In [ ]:
model = Sequential()
model.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 1)))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
model.add(BatchNormalization())

model.add(Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
model.add(BatchNormalization())

model.add(Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
model.add(BatchNormalization())

model.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
model.add(BatchNormalization())

model.add(Dropout(0.2))

model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(39, activation = 'softmax')) #number of level2 label

#compilation
model.compile(optimizer='adam', 
          loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
          metrics=['accuracy'])

In [75]:
from sklearn.utils.multiclass import unique_labels

def plot_confusion_matrix2(y_true, y_pred, classes, size, text=True,
                          normalize=False,
                          title=None,
                          cmap=plt.cm.YlOrRd):

    y_true=y_true.reshape(-1)
    if not title:
        if normalize:
            title = 'Normalized confusion matrix'
        else:
            title = 'Confusion matrix, without normalization'

    # Compute confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    # Only use the labels that appear in the data
    classes = classes[unique_labels(y_true, y_pred)]
    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        print("Normalized confusion matrix")
    else:
        print('Confusion matrix, without normalization')

    print(cm)

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(size,size))
    im = ax.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    ax.figure.colorbar(im, ax=ax,)
    # We want to show all ticks...
    ax.set(xticks=np.arange(cm.shape[1]),
           yticks=np.arange(cm.shape[0]),
           # ... and label them with the respective list entries
           xticklabels=classes, yticklabels=classes,
           title=title,
           ylabel='True label',
           xlabel='Predicted label')

    # Rotate the tick labels and set their alignment.
    plt.setp(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=90, ha="right",
             rotation_mode="anchor")

    # Loop over data dimensions and create text annotations.
    if text==True:
        fmt = '.2f' if normalize else 'd'
        thresh = cm.max() / 2.
        for i in range(cm.shape[0]):
            for j in range(cm.shape[1]):
                if cm[i,j]>0:
                    ax.text(j, i, format(cm[i, j], fmt),ha="center", va="center",color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")
        fig.tight_layout()
    return ax

This confusion matrix allows us to see how the labels have been predicted for each class.

First of all, we can notice that our model is not good, indeed the diagonal coefficients of this matrix are very bad, which means that for each class, only few images have been correctly classified.

Secondly, we see that some labels lead to confusion. Some columns of the matrix are totally coloured which means that the label of this column has been predicted at least once for a different label. For instance, regarding the 'detritus' column, we can see many images have been classified as detritus. This is due to the important proportion of detritus images (;ore than 50% of the dataset). We can also observe it for the Neoceratium which is the most represented plankton of the dataset. To solve this issue, we will increase the proportion of the less frequent plankton images.

    training_data_set_size = parameter_combination['datasetSize']

    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = get_train_test_sets(X_small,Y_small,IMG_SIZE)
        
    t0 = time()
    
    #fitting the model
    model.fit(x_train,y_train,validation_data=(x_test,y_test),batch_size = parameter_combination['batchSize'], epochs = parameter_combination['epochNb'], verbose = 1)

    #get results

We forgot to sort the dataframe while the kernel was running, but we can clearly see that for the same parameters, images of 100x100 give better results that 50x50 images, but the computation time is multiplied by 4.

However, we are able to double our accuracy! Let's analyse our results:

  • A batchsize of 100 instead of 50: suprisingly, the model gives faster and better results! but let's keep in mind that we take small and differents subsets each time, so the results might be biased from one subset to another. But a crossvalidation would take quite some time so we decided not to do it.
  • 3 or 5 epochs: The algorithm seems to still learns after 3 epochs (lignes 2 and 6), but the computation time of course increase proportionnaly to the number of epochs.
  • Size of images side: 50 or 100? let's look at the lignes 7 and 8: the performances don't increase with the size! Even though for other parameters (lignes 2 and 11), the f1 score increases, the computation time goes really high (from 63s to 300s).
  • Size of the dataset: As for the rest, increasing the dataset size improves the performance but increases the computation size.

Test of different architectures

We optimized the hyperparameters of almost random model we found on the internet. Now, we have to adapt the model to our dataset. Let's analyse our convolutionnal neural network. We have several different types of layers:

  • Conv2 layer: using a certain number of kernel, this layer will compute the convolution of our images and the kernel to put the image information into different blocks. For example one kernel will give information direction of the lines. This is the most important type of layer in our model and it has some parameters to fix, such as the number of kernel and their size which will have impact on the amount and accuracy of the information.
  • Pooling layer: The goal of this layer is to avoid overfitting by down-sampling the output of the previous layers. There are two main ways to do so: taking the maximum or the average of the pixel values of some 'pool' which size we can control.
  • BatchNormalization: This layer is used to avoid to big number and keep the values in a good scale.
  • Dropout: drop some output to prevent overfitting.

In the end of the convolutionnal network, we have to cast our 2D output into our level2 labels. In other words: now that we have tranformed our image to real infomation (like where the lines are, how many they are, and so on and so forth), we need a real neural network to learn from this information and link them to the labels.

In addition to the layer parameters, we can control the number of layers or group of layers. In the end, it is a lot of hyper parameters and we couldn't test them all. However we managed to improve our results.

#Instantiate an empty model
model_LeNet = Sequential()

# C1 Convolutional Layer
model_LeNet.add(Conv2D(6, kernel_size=(5, 5), strides=(1, 1), activation='tanh',input_shape=(IMG_SIZE,IMG_SIZE,1), padding='same'))
# S2 Pooling Layer
model_LeNet.add(AveragePooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), strides=(1, 1), padding='valid'))

# C3 Convolutional Layer
model_LeNet.add(Conv2D(16, kernel_size=(5, 5), strides=(1, 1), activation='tanh', padding='valid'))
# S4 Pooling Layer
model_LeNet.add(AveragePooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), strides=(2, 2), padding='valid'))

# C5 Fully Connected Convolutional Layer
model_LeNet.add(Conv2D(120, kernel_size=(5, 5), strides=(1, 1), activation='tanh', padding='valid'))
#Flatten the CNN output so that we can connect it with fully connected layers
model_LeNet.add(Flatten())

# FC6 Fully Connected Layer
model_LeNet.add(Dense(84, activation='tanh'))

#Output Layer with softmax activation
model_LeNet.add(Dense(39, activation='softmax'))

# Compile the model
model_LeNet.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='SGD', metrics=['accuracy'])

Even by changing the kernel size, the size of the output space, the activation function and the hyperparameters of the fit function, we couldn't reach as good results as with our previous model.

So we chose the following parameters for the fit function:

  • Number of epoch: 5
  • Batch size: 100
  • img_size: 50
  • dataset size: 10 000

Se we came back to our model and modified the arguments of the Conv2D layer, and the number of Dropout layers. Adding dropout between the two convolutional layers reduced a lot our score (always under 0.2) even it also reduced the time of computation. Increasing the output space of the conv2d layers increased a lot the computation time while not giving a good score: with output space of 160, 80 and 64, the model only reached a score of 0.11 in 6min!

Model choice

Finally, we chose the model which gave us the best results:

Fortunatly, the diagonal is much more red than for our first model! This shows that our classifier is quite good. Even if the score is biased by some categories which are badly predicted, such as the danicus (last one), our classifier is able to predict more than 40 percent of most the classes. Still, a lot of images are wrongly classified as detritus but it is not really surprising since 50 percent of our dataset belong to this class.
